          "body": "Verses 3-8 narrate the most solemn legal act in Israel's history: the ratification of the Mosaic Covenant. The sequence is exact and irreversible. Moses first proclaims all the LORD's words and ordinances (v. 3); the people pledge their obedience with one voice. Moses writes everything down (v. 4) — the written document is the covenant's durable witness. The altar is built, sacrifices are offered (vv. 4-5), and the blood is divided: half on the altar, half reserved in basins. Then the Book of the Covenant is read publicly a second time (v. 7), and the people pledge again with intensified language — 'we will do and be obedient.' Only then does Moses apply the blood to the people (v. 8), declaring: 'Behold the blood of the covenant which the LORD has made with you in accordance with all these words.' The blood enacts what the words have declared. Both parties — God (the altar represents His side) and Israel (the people receive the blood) — are now bound by the same life-and-death sanction. This is the Old Testament's clearest anticipation of the New Covenant's blood ratification: Jesus at the Last Supper takes 'the cup of the new covenant in My blood' (Luke 22:20; 1 Corinthians 11:25) and says 'this is My blood of the covenant, poured out for many for forgiveness of sins' (Matthew 26:28), deliberately echoing Moses's exact words in verse 8."
